<Content>A wonderful retreat My freind and I just returned from Barcelona yesterday. We planed to be frugal...not an easy task in Barcelona. So, initially we stayed at what turned out to be a disastrous choice, the guesthouse Solyk in the Barri Gotic .FYI- the Barric Gotic is a very beautiful area, but if you want to sleep do not stay in this barrio...pick a quieter more remote location. Don't limit yourself. Gracia is literally 5 minutes away from this location and the metro system is the best and easiest I've experienced in Europe. You can easily get anywhere very fast. Trains run on the dot every 5 minutes.For 75 euros (approx.$100 dollars/night) Solyk offered a sparsely furnished small room....no common area with soft drinks, tea/coffee and a place to relax, only small hand towels in the private bath, and the clincher was there was no phone on the premises and noone available on site during the evening and through most of the day. There were no maps or tourist info. available anywhere. Just lots of advertisments and magazines pertaining to the gay lifestyle. There were no pictures adorning walls....and the lights were always off when we came in. It was deplorable. When we had to implore the guesthouse manager to call the police to chase away the drunken vagrants perched outside on a mattress in front of the building, we decided to look for new accomidations asap. In the Gracia area...a lovely residential, albeit packed with quaint stores, restaurants and beautiful architecture...and close to Guell Park. we found the wonderful Aparthotel Silver. For only 5 euros more...that's right, 80 euros/night which is a great deal in Barcelona, we got a room with kitchenette, TV, phone, full bath, quiet, fantastic location and hotel ammenities including free internet access in the lobby. Unfortunately the 80 euros/night room was not available for the duration of our stay so we opted to take the only other room available which was their suite for 120 euros/night. It was nirvana! A huge terrace with outdoor chairs and tables to eat your breakfast. A lovely huge space of blond wood, a sofa, 2 full beds, TV, stereo, phone, gorgeous huge bath and full kitchenette with microwave, dishes, cutlery, etc. Best of all we could finally have a noiseless night of sleep. Another great benefit of staying at Aparthotel Silver is the breakfast they serve for 6.5 euros. Food is quite expensive in Barcelona. Even buying staples at grocery stores was costly. The breakfast they offer is a fantastic value that we could not find elsewhere. For 6.5 euros they serve coffee, a buffet of fruits, a spread of breakfast cheeses, meats, salad and sliced egg, croissants, rolls, sliced bread and pastries. It was all fresh, plentiful and very tasty. This meal is all you can eat and can tide you over for many hours of exploring the city. This hotel is located at the Fontana station on the green line...extremely accessable by metro and bus and close to all attractions, but remote enough to be more relaxed to get a feel of another side of Barcelona. And there's a beautiful Gaudi house, literally right around the corner! The staff was always lovely and very helpful. I highly recomment the Aparthotel Silver. 
